  "prompt": "What is Goldman Sachs discretionary compensation structure (preferably by division)?",
  "response": "Goldman Sachs' discretionary compensation structure varies by division and is typically influenced by factors such as individual performance, divisional performance, and overall firm profitability. Compensation at Goldman Sachs generally consists of a **base salary** and a **discretionary bonus**, with the bonus being a significant portion of total pay, especially for senior employees. Below is an overview of how compensation typically breaks down by division, though specific numbers can vary widely depending on the year, role, and revenue generated:\n\n### 1. **Investment Banking (IBD)**  \n   - Base Salary: $100K\u2013$200K (analysts/associates) to $400K+ (MDs)  \n   - Bonus: Typically 50%\u2013200% of base salary, depending on deal flow, individual performance, and revenue. Senior bankers may receive bonuses that are multiples of their base salary.  \n   - Total Compensation: $150K\u2013$400K (analysts/associates) to $1M+ (MDs).  \n\n### 2. **Global Markets (Sales & Trading)**  \n   - Base Salary: $100K\u2013$300K (analysts/associates) to $500K+ (MDs)  \n   - Bonus: Heavily tied to revenue generated and market conditions. Can range from 50%\u2013300% of base salary.  \n   - Total Compensation: $150K\u2013$500K (junior roles) to $2M+ (senior traders/desk heads).  \n\n### 3. **Asset Management (AM)**  \n   - Base Salary: $100K\u2013$200K (analysts/associates) to $400K+ (MDs)  \n   - Bonus: Typically 30%\u2013150% of base salary, depending on AUM growth, fund performance, and revenue.  \n   - Total Compensation: $150K\u2013$400K (junior roles) to $1M+ (senior roles).  \n\n### 4. **Private Wealth Management (PWM)**  \n   - Base Salary: $100K\u2013$200K (analysts/associates) to $300K+ (MDs)  \n   - Bonus: Tied to client acquisition, AUM, and revenue. Can range from 30%\u2013200% of base salary.  \n   - Total Compensation: $150K\u2013$400K (junior roles) to $1M+ (senior advisors).  \n\n### 5. **Technology**  \n   - Base Salary: $100K\u2013$200K (junior engineers) to $300K+ (senior roles)  \n   - Bonus: Typically 20%\u2013100% of base salary, depending on project impact and performance.  \n   - Total Compensation: $150K\u2013$400K (junior roles) to $600K+ (senior roles).  \n\n### 6. **Operations, Risk, and Compliance**  \n   - Base Salary: $80K\u2013$150K (junior roles) to $300K+ (senior roles)  \n   - Bonus: Typically 10%\u201350% of base salary.  \n   - Total Compensation: $100K\u2013$400K (senior roles).  \n\n### Key Factors Influencing Compensation:  \n1. **Revenue Generation**: Front-office roles like IBD and Sales & Trading are more directly tied to revenue and typically receive higher bonuses.  \n2. **Performance**: Individual and team performance plays a significant role.  \n3. **Market Conditions**: Bonuses in divisions like Sales & Trading can vary widely depending on market performance.  \n4. **Seniority**: More senior roles (e.g., Managing Directors, Partners) receive a larger share of discretionary compensation.  \n\n### Note:  \nThese figures are approximate and can vary significantly year-to-year based on the firm\u2019s performance and market conditions. Goldman Sachs, like other Wall Street firms, adjusts its compensation structure annually to align with profitability and competitive pressures.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
